{
  "texts": [
    "Many audio signals contain prominent oscillatory components as a direct consequence of the physical tendency of objects to produce periodic vibrations (Smith, 2010).",
    "A natural choice for modelling such signals, additive synthesis, thus also encodes such a preference for oscillation.",
    "Motivated by the signal processing interpretation of Fourier's theorem, i.e., that a signal can be decomposed into sinusoidal components, additive synthesis describes a signal as a finite sum of sinusoidal components.",
    "Unlike representation in the discrete Fourier basis, however, the frequency axis is not necessarily discretised, allowing for direct specification of component frequencies.",
    "The general form for such a model in discrete time is thus:"
  ]
}